#3) Split data into test and training set

split1<- sample(c(rep('Train', 0.8 * nrow(parkinsons_updrs)), 
                  rep('Test', 0.2 * nrow(parkinsons_updrs))))
table(split1)
## split1
##  Test Train 
##  1175  4700
x_train<-parkinsons_updrs[split1=='Train', ]
total_UPDRS_train <- x_train$total_UPDRS
motor_UPDRS_train <- x_train$motor_UPDRS
x_train<- subset(x_train, select = -c(total_UPDRS,motor_UPDRS))
attach(x_train)
## The following objects are masked from parkinsons_updrs:
## 
##     age, DFA, HNR, Jitter:DDP, Jitter:PPQ5, Jitter:RAP, Jitter(%),
##     Jitter(Abs), NHR, PPE, RPDE, sex, Shimmer, Shimmer:APQ11,
##     Shimmer:APQ3, Shimmer:APQ5, Shimmer:DDA, Shimmer(dB), subject#,
##     test_time
x_test<-parkinsons_updrs[split1=='Test', ]
total_UPDRS_test <- x_test$total_UPDRS
motor_UPDRS_test <- x_test$motor_UPDRS
x_test <- subset(x_test, select = -c(total_UPDRS,motor_UPDRS))

With the data split in to 80 20 4700 of the examples will be used for training and 1175 examples will be used for testing.

#4 Build a multiple linear regression containing all input variables to predict total_UPDRS

parkinsons_model <- lm(total_UPDRS_train~ age+test_time+sex
                       +`Jitter(Abs)`+ `Jitter:RAP`+`Jitter:DDP`+`Jitter:PPQ5`
                       +Shimmer+`Shimmer(dB)`+`Shimmer:APQ3`+`Shimmer:DDA`
                       +`Shimmer:APQ5`+`Shimmer:APQ11`+ NHR+HNR
                       +RPDE+(`Jitter(%)`)+DFA+PPE, data = x_train)
summary(parkinsons_model)

The predictors that have significant impact on the model are sex, test_time, Jitter(Abs), NHR, HNR, DFA and PPE. This is known becasue these predictors all have the lowest pvalues.
RSE = 9.671 Rsquared = 0.1824 This is a very high RSE and a very low rsquared value indicating that this is not a good model. If ‘Subject #’ is included it will have better RSE and Rsquared values, but the Subject # intuitively is not useful in making these predictions.

#7 Show Diagnostic plots of all three models above. As you can see by the rsquared values mentioned above there is not much movement in the performance. This being said: The main plot to look at in the shown diagnostic plots are the residuals vs fitted plots. In this plot, a perfect model will have a completely straight trend line. You can clearly see the trend line straightening from the fitted vs residuals plot in the first model to that in the interactions model

This supports the evidence provided by the rsquared values.
